=== Lesson 32-2 (Step-by-Step Approach) ===

 {"type":"h3","text":"Step-by-Step Approach"}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 1: Identify the Specific Person or Group"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Read the question stem carefully to identify the exact third party..."}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 2: Locate All Mentions and Attributions"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Scan the passage for the name or description of the party from Step 1..."}
 {"type":"list","items":["\"Smith argues that...\"","\"According to the critics...\"","\"Proponents of this view claim...\""]}

{ "type": "diff-note", "text": "The attribution phrase examples are concrete and well-chosen. Students should internalize these as 'search targets' when scanning the passage.", "variant": "comment" }

 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 3: Isolate and Paraphrase Their Viewpoint"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Focus only on the text directly linked to the third party...Crucially, ignore what the author thinks about their view..."}
+{{+**Missing:** Add an example showing how author commentary around a third-party claim can mislead. E.g., "The passage says: 'Critics argue that digital archives are unreliable. While this concern has some merit, the evidence overwhelmingly supports...' Here, 'this concern has some merit' is the AUTHOR's commentary, not the critics' view. The critics' actual claim is only: 'digital archives are unreliable.'"+}}
 {"type":"h4","text":"Step 4: Match Your Paraphrase to the Answer Choices"}
 {"type":"paragraph","text":"Compare your understanding of the third party's viewpoint to each answer choice..."}
+{{+**Cross-reference:** The "Check Ownership" skill in Module 30 (Author Viewpoint) is the flip side of this module's attribution-tracking skill. Module 30 warns against accidentally selecting a third party's view when the question asks for the author's view. This module teaches the reverse: accurately isolating the third party's view from author commentary. Together, these modules build a unified perspective-tracking skill.+}}
